NMAP – PORT SCANNING

-  By default       Scans top 1000 ports [here this 1000 is commonly used ones not    the sequential ones].
-  By default       By default, Nmap performs a TCP SYN scan for privileged users (root/admin).



•	nmap -F target_IP
-   To scan top 100 ports.
-   F   Faster, Fewer.

•	nmap -p specific_port target_IP
•	nmap -p specific_port_1, specific_port_2, ….
•	nmap -p port_range
-   To scan specific port, based on port no.

•	nmap -p ‘*’ target_IP     [ OR ]     nmap -p- target_IP
-   To scan all ports of target ip.

NOTE : COMBINING 2 PROTOCOLS  nmap -sU -sT -p U:53, T:25 target_IP

•	nmap --top-ports count target_IP
-   Used to scan top few_ports [This count is of your choice].

•	nmap -r target_IP
-   Used to scan ports in sequential order.





NMAP – FOUNDATIONAL SCANNING – HOST DISCOVERY


•	nmap -Pn target_IP
-   Used to skip host discovery(ping) and assume the target is alive.
-   Normally nmap 1st pings, but here it’s neglected.
-   DON’T PING.

•	nmap -Sn target_IP
-   Used to perform ping scan to discover live hosts, without scanning ports.
-   PING ONLY SCAN. ICMP protocol.
•	nmap -PS target_IP
-   To perform host discovery by sending TCP SYN packets to determine whether the target system is alive or not – without relying on ICMP protocol, use TCP SYN – TCP SYN PING.

•	nmap -PA target_IP
-   To perform host discovery by sending TCP ACK packets to determine whether the target system is alive or not.
-   No ICMP, uses TCP ACK


NOTE : 
1)	-sS      Performs TCP connect port scan to identify open ports.
2)	-PS     Performs TCP SYN ping to discover whether a host is alive or not.

TO BE REMEMBERED : 
1)	-PA    Uses TCP ACK packets to check whether a host is alive or not [ACK ping]
2)	-PS    Uses TCP SYN packets to check whether a host is alive or not [SYN ping]
3)	-sT     Performs a TCP connect scan to identify open ports using a full TCP handshake.
4)	-sS     Performs a TCP SYN (Stealth scan) to identify open ports without completing the TCP connection.
5)	-PU    Uses UDP ping packets to check whether a host is alive or not [UDP ping]
6)	-sU    Performs a UDP port scan to identify open UDP services on the targe.


•	nmap -PU target_IP
-   Uses UDP ping packets to check whether a host is alive or not.


NOTES : 
1)	TCP     Reliable, one path     Web / Mail / File.
2)	UDP    Not Reliable, fast       Fast streaming / Game / Voice.


•	nmap -PE target_IP
-   Uses ICMP echo request (ping) to check whether a host is alive.

•	nmap -PP target_IP
-   Uses ICMP timestamp request to check if the host is alive or not.

NOTE : 
1)	-PE      Uses ICMP Echo Request for host discovery.
2)	-PP      Uses ICMP Timestamp Request.

  ICMP Timestamp Request – It’s a packet sent to a host asking for it’s current system   time, used in host discovery & OS fingerprinting.


•	nmap -PM target_IP
-   Uses ICMP address Mask Request to check whether a host is alive.

•	nmap -PO target_IP
-   Uses IP protocol ping to check whether a host is alive.
-   Instead of TCP / UDP / ICMP, nmap sends raw IP packet using different IP protocol numbers.
-   PO without a number = ICMP by default.

•	nmap -PR target_IP
-   Uses ARP request to discover live hosts on a local network.
-   Target is in the same subnet / same LAN.
-   Won’t work over the internet or routed network.

•	nmap --traceroute target_IP
-   Shows the network path (hops) from your machine to the target.
-   Protocols used      UDP, TCP or ICMP.
-   If ICMP is blocked, Nmap traceroute may still work using TCP / UDP.

•	nmap -R <target_IP>
-   Forces reverse DNS lookup to resolve IP address into hostnames.

•	nmap -n <target_IP>
-   Disable DNS resolution.



NOTE : DIFFERENCE BETWEEN -n & -R
	-n   -  Do not resolve IP to hostnames.
	-R   -  Force hostname resolution even if disabled by default.


•	nmap --system-dns <target_ip> 
-   Tells nmap to use the OS’s default DNS resolver instead of its own internal DNS engine.

•	nmap --dns-servers _____, _____, ____ <target_IP>
-   Tells Nmap to use specific DNS servers you choose for name resolution.

WORKFLOW : 
1)	You run the command and specify DNS server (Ex : 8.8.8.8 / 1.1.1.1)
2)	Nmap ignores system DNS settings
3)	Sends DNS queries only to the given servers.
4)	DNS server replies with hostname (if available).
5)	Nmap uses that name in scan output & continues scanning.

  This is a DNS resolution query which only adds a name to the IP, it does not creates a new scan target.



SUM-UP DNS LOOKUP
1)	Default	-	Nmap’s internal DNS.
2)	-n		-	No DNS.
3)	-R		-	Force DNS.
4)	--System-dns				-	OS DNS resolver.
5)	--dns-servers <server1, server2>	-	Use specific DNS server.





ADVANCED SCANNING


1)	TCP SYN SCAN [Default for PRIVELEGED USERS – ROOT/ADMIN]
 -    nmap -sS <target_IP>
o	To identify open TCP ports on a target system without completing a full TCP connection.

2)	TCP CONNECT SCAN [Default for NON-PRIVELEGED USERS]
-   nmap -sT <target_IP>
o	To identify open TCP ports on a target system by completing the fall TCP 3-way handshake.

3)	UDP SCAN
-   nmap -sU <target_IP>
o	To identify open or filtered UDP ports on a target system by sending UDP packets & analysing the responses.

4)	TCP NULL SCAN
-   nmap -sN <target_IP>
o	To identify open or filtered TCP ports by sending TCP packets with no flags set (NULL SCAN) to bypass basic firewall rules.

5)	TCP FIN SCAN
-   nmap -sF <target_IP>
o	To identify open or filtered TCP ports by sending TCP FIN packets and analysing the response, often to evade(escape) simple firewall filtering.

6)	TCP XMAS SCAN
-   nmap -sX <target_IP>
o	To identify open or filtered TCP ports by sending TCP packets with FIN, PSH & URG flags set (XMAS SCAN) to bypass basic firewall rules.

7)	TCP ACK SCAN
-   nmap -sA <target_IP>
o	GOAL : To check whether a firewall is blocking a port or letting traffic through, no whether the port is open.
o	WHAT RESPONSES MEAN : 
          -   RST reply : Firewall lets traffic through    UNFILTERED.
          -   No reply / ICMP error : Firewall blocked it     FILTERED.

NOTE : -sA IS USED TO MAP FIREWALL RULES, NOT TO DISCOVER OPEN PORTS.

8)	CUSTOM TCP SCAN [ACK, SYN, FIN, PSH, URG & RST]
-   nmap --scanflags {flag/s} {target_IP}
o	To perform a custom TCP SCAN by manually specifying which TCP flags are set in probe packets, allowing flexible & evasion scanning.
o	REAL-LIFE : You knock on a door using a strange pattern; The reaction tells you how strict the guard is.
o	Requires privileged user(root) / works only for TCP.

9)	IP PROTOCOL SCAN
-   nmap -sO <target_IP>
o	To identify which IP protocols (like TCP, UDP, ICMP, SCTP) are supported by the target system.
o	Instead of scanning ports, Nmap scans IP protocol numbers.

o	It checks what protocols the host understands
EX :       1             ICMP
           6             TCP
           17            UDP
           132           SCTP


10)	SEND RAW ETHERNET PACKETS
-    nmap --send-eth <target_IP>
o	To force Nmap to send packets at the ethernet (layer 2) level instead of the IP (layer 3) level.

11)	SEND IP PACKETS
-   nmap --send-ip <target_IP>
o	To force Nmap to send packets at the IP layers (layer 3) instead of the ethernet layer, letting the OS handle ethernet framing.





OS & SERVICE DETECTION

1)	OS DETECTION
-   nmap -O <target_IP>
o	To identify the OS of the target host by analysing TCP/IP stack behaviour (OS fingerprinting).

2)	OS DETECTION (OS SCAN LIMIT QUERY)
-   nmap -O --osscan-limit <target_IP>
o	To limit OS detection attempts only to targets that are likely to provide accurate OS fingerprinting results.

3)	OS DETECTION (OS SCAN GUESS QUERY)
-   nmap -O --osscan-guess <target_IP>
o	To make Nmap aggressively guess the targets OS even when the OS fingerprint match is weak or incomplete.

NOTE : 
  --osscan-limit   -  If I can’t detect OS properly, don’t even try.
  --osscan-guess – Try anyway & show me your best guess.



		-   nmap -O --fuzzy <target_IP>
o	This is similar to that or the nmap -O --osscan-guess, but the fuzzy is the older version.

4)	VERSION DETECTION
-   nmap -sV <target_IP>
o	To identify the service name & version running on open ports of the target system.

5)	VERSION DETECTION (IN-DEPTH)
-   nmap -sV --version-trace <target_IP>
o	To show exactly how Nmap performs service version detection step-by-step.





TIMING OPTIONS

1)	TIMING PARAMETERS
-   nmap -T5  <target_IP>
o	Controls how fast or slow [0 – 5] Nmap scans the target by adjusting timing and stealth.

o	NOTE :     0 – Extremely slow …….. ; 5 – Very fast, noisy.
 				     If -T ___  is not specified, Nmap uses -T4 (normal).

2)	MINIMUM & MAXIMUM NUMBER OF PARALLEL OPERATION
-   nmap --min-parallelism num <targetIP>
o	Forces Nmap to send atleast num probes simultaneously.

-   nmap --max-parallelism num <target_IP>
o	Limits Nmap to send at most num probes at a time.

NOTE : 
  A probe is a packet or request that Nmap sends to a target to get information.
  By default, Nmap dynamically adjust the number of parallel probes based on network conditions.

3)	MINIMUM & MAXIMUM HOST GROUP SIZE
-   nmap --min-hostgroup <num> <target_IP>
o	Forces Nmap to scan atleast <num> hosts at the same time.

-   nmap --max-hostgroup <num> <target_IP>
o	Limits Nmap to scan at most <num> hosts simultaneously.

NOTE : 
  Host group controls how many targets are scanned concurrently, while probes control how many packets are sent concurrently, while probes control how many packets are sent concurrently.

  For both --max-hostgroup & --min-hostgroup – it’s meaningful only when you provide multiple targets, so instead of a single target_IP, you should give a subnet, IP range, or host list.



4)	(i) INITIAL RTT TIMEOUT 

[ RTT => Round Trip Time – Time for a packet to go to the target & come back]


	-   nmap --initial-rtt-timeout <time> <target_IP>
o	Sets the initial wait time Nmap uses to receive response from the target before adjusting dynamically.
o	Nmap initially waits 100 MS for response.
o	Time specification : ms, s, m or h [ But typically in ms].


      (ii) MAX RTT TIMEOUT
-   nmap --max-rtt-timeout <time> <target_IP>
o	Nmap will not wait longer than this.

      (iii) MIN RTT TIMEOUT
	-   nmap --min-rtt-timeout <time> <target_IP>
o	Nmap will never wait less than this, no matter how fast replies seem.


NOTE : 
DIFFERENCE BETWEEN : 
1)	INITIAL RTT
         -   Used only for the first few probes.
	       -   Can increase / decrease later.
2)  MIN / MAX RTT
	       -   Applies throughout the scan.
	       -   Nmap will never go below this value.



DIFFERENCE BETWEEN : 
1)	RTT
    -   Controls how long Nmap waits for a reply to each probe.
    -   How long you wait at a traffic signal.
2)  -T
		-   Controls overall scan aggressiveness & speed.
		-   Ex : How fast you decide to drive overall.


5)	MAXIMUM RETRIES

-   nmap --max-retries <number> <target_IP>
o	Sets the maximum number of times Nmap will retransmit a probe if no response is received.

-   nmap --min-retries <number> <target_IP>
o	Forces Nmap to retry each unanswered probe atleast <number> times before giving up.

NOTE : BY DEFAULT, NMAP AUTOMATICALLY ADJUSTS THE NUMBER OF RETRIES BASED ON NETWORK CONDITIONS.



6)	SET THE PACKET TTL

TTL – TIME TO LIVE    IT’S NOT A TIME, IT’S THE HOP COUNT
-   nmap --ttl <number> <target_IP>
o	Defines the maximum number of hops Nmap packets can traverse before being discarded.


WHAT’S TTL : 
	-   TTL = Maximum number of network hops a packet can travel.
	-   Each router reduces TTL by 1.
	-   When TTL reaches 0, the packet is dropped.


7)	HOST TIMEOUT

-   nmap --host-timeout <time> <target_IP>
o	Sets the maximum total time Nmap will spend scanning a single host before giving up.
o	Time formats : ms, s, m, h.

BY DEFAULT, NMAP DOES NOT IMPOSE A HOST TIMEOUT & SCANS A HOST UNTIL COMPLETION.

NOTE – DIFFERENCE BETWEEN PROBE vs HOST
I)	PROBE  -  A single packet or request Nmap sends to ask a question.
II)	HOST     -  One target system (IP) being scanned.



8)	MINIMUM & MAXIMUM SCAN DELAY

-   nmap --scan-delay <time> <target_IP>
o	Force Nmap to wait at least <time> between consecutive probes.

-    nmap --min-scan-delay <time> <target_IP>
o	Sets the minimum pause Nmap must wait between probes.

-   nmap --max-scan-delay <time> <target_IP>
o	Sets the maximum pause Nmap is allowed to wait between probes.


NOTE : THERE IS NO FIXED NUMBER OF PROBES PER HOST; IT DEPENDS ON SCAN TYPE, PORT RANGE & RETRIES.


9)	MINIMUM & MAXIMUM PACKET RATE

-    nmap --min-rate <number> <target_IP>
o	Forces Nmap to send at least <number> probes per second.

-   nmap --max-rate <number> <target_IP>
o	Forces Nmap to send at most <number> probes per second.

-   nmap --max-rate 0.1 <target_IP>        [ SPECIAL CASE]
o	1 packet every 10 seconds.
o	Extreme stealth / very sensitive networks.

NOTE : THERE’S NO DEFAULT RATE VALUE; DYNAMICALLY ADJUSTS PACKET RATE BASED ON : RTT, -T, HOST RESPONSE ETC..


10)	DEFEAT RESET RATE LIMITS

-   nmap --defeat-rst-ratelimit <target_IP>
o	To accurately identify open TCP ports on systems/firewalls
o	Helps Nmap not get confused when the target sends “ too many No responses too slowly”.





