NAVIGATING FIREWALLS

1)	FRAGMENTING CUSTOM MTU [Maximum Transmission Unit] FOR EVASION
-    nmap --mtu <number> <target_IP>
o	--mtu makes Nmap split packets into smaller fragments to try to bypass firewalls.
o	MAIN PURPOSE : To bypass firewalls / IDS / IPS that block or inspect normal packets
o	<number>   =>   Tells the size of each packet’s fragment.
o	BY DEFAULT, NMAP SENDS COMPLETE PACKETS WITHOUT FRAGMENTATION.

NOTE : - MTU CONTROLS FRAGMENT SIZE ; SMALLER FRAGMENTS MAY EVADE WEAK FIREWALL BUT CAN ALERT MODERN IDS.


2)	DECOY SCANNING FOR ANONYMITY
-    nmap -D <Decoys / RND : (num) > <target_IP>
o	Hide the real attacker IP by mixing it with fake (decoy) IP addresses.
o	If you don’t specify <num>, By default Nmap uses 10 random decoy IP  10 random decoys + your real IP = 11 scources reaches the target.
o	Decoy IPs are spoofed source addresses used only to confuse logs they don’t receive scan results & aren’t actively involved.

3)	IDEL ZOMBIE SCAN
-   nmap -sI <zombie_Host> <target_IP>
o	Idle zombie scan uses an Idle 3rd system’s IP ID behaviour to infer open ports on a target without ever touching it directly.
o	This scan is reliable only when the zombie host is truly idle; any external traffic invalidates IP ID-based inference
o	THERE’S NO DEFAULT ZOMBIE HOST IN NMAP.

4)	MANUALLY SPECIFY SOURCE PORT NUMBER
-   nmap --source-port <port_num> <target_IP>
o	This is used to evade simple port-based filtering by making scan traffic appear to originate from a trusted service port.
o	Nmap sends scan packets with the source port spoofed to the specified port number instead of using a random high port.
o	To bypass weak firewall or all rules that allow traffic from trusted source ports [ Eg : 53,443, 80 …]
                      SHORTCUT QUERY : 
		-   nmap -g <port_num> <target_IP>

5)	APPEND RANDOM DATA 
-   nmap --data-length <num> <target_IP>
o	To evade IDS / IPS and signature-based detection by making    scan packets look non-standard.
o	<num> => Nmap adds <num> bytes of random data to each packet, increasing the packet size.
o	Padding is used only to evade simple signature-based detection system.

6)	RANDOMIZE TARGET SCAN ORDER
-   nmap --randomize-hosts <target_IP>
o	Randomizes the order in which multiple target hosts are scanned.
o	It’s useful because    without this it’s easy for IDS to notice a sequential scan pattern.
o	This only makes same when scanning multiple hosts.

7)	SPOOFING MAC ADDRESS
-   nmap --spoof-mac <MAC / vender/ 0> <target_IP>
o	Changes (spoofs) the MAC address used by Nmap during the scan.
o	IT WORKS ONLY ON LOCAL NETWORK BECAUSE MAC ADDRESS ARE NOT PRESERVED ACROSS ROUTERS.

8)	SEND BAD CHECKSUMS
-   nmap --badsum <target_IP>
o	Sends packets with an intentionally incorrect TCP / UDP checksum.
o	It sends invalid packets to see how security device react, not to find open port.
o	PURPOSE : TO TEST OR EVADE POORLY CONFIGURED FIREWALLS & IDS.





NMAP SCRIPT ENGINE


1)	EXECUTE INDIVIDUAL SCRIPTS
-  COMMON TEMPLATE : nmap --script <scripts> <target_IP>
o	Tells Nmap to run NSE scripts for automates recon, detection or exploitation tasks.


EX – 1 : TO GET INFORMATION FROM WHOIS RECORDS
-   nmap -sn --script whois-*  <target>
o	To gather WHOIS & registration-related information about the target without scanning ports.


EX – 2 : TRACEROUTE – GEOLOCATION
-    nmap --traceroute --script traceroute-geolocation <target_IP>
o	This command shows how packets reach the target and where each hop is located geographically.





CONCLUSION

Nmap is one of the most powerful and widely used network scanning and security auditing tools in cybersecurity and ethical hacking. It helps security professionals identify live hosts, open ports, running services, operating systems, network paths, and potential vulnerabilities within a target environment. Understanding Nmap scanning techniques, discovery methods, timing options, firewall evasion techniques, and NSE scripting provides a strong foundation for network reconnaissance and penetration testing. Proper knowledge and ethical usage of Nmap are essential for performing effective security assessments and strengthening overall network security.
